      </image>

      <p>
        Now suppose a person has to go from <term>city A</term> to <term>city C</term>. But he has two choices to reach to <term>city C</term>. 
        He can go either  via <term>city B</term> or via <term>city D</term> as shown in figure below. There are <m>m</m> ways (roads) to go from 
    <term>city A</term> to <term>city C</term> via <term>city B</term> and <m>n</m> ways to go from <term>city A</term> to <term>city C</term> 
    via <term>city D</term>, then total number of ways he can go from <term>city A</term> to <term>city C</term> is given by <m>m + n.</m> 
    Here, the person can reach to <term>city C</term> from <term>city A</term> either by going through <term>city B</term> <em>or</em> 
    by going through <term>city D</term>. So the each part of work is not compulsory to him. Hence, we use the principle of addition.
      </p>

